column2: Hot- sunny- mild breeze- no recent rain.
Weather is sunny- moderate wave action- moderate boating activity last rain was about 2" on 8/6/86.
Partly sunny- warm- and no obvious algae.
Sunny and hot.  There is little boat traffic.
Warm- partly cloudy- little boat traffic.
Clear- sunny day- few boats- water has been very green for the past three weeks.
Sunny- windy- and cool around 65 degrees.
Lots of weeds--milfoil- water remarkably clear in weed beds.
Sunny and pleasant; perception due to weeds.
Perception due to weeds--says to discount reading because of weeds.
Couldn't take reading because of weeds.
Perception due to weeds which are real bad.
West Lobe of lake is turning green.
Although the perception is 3- the deep parts are okay to swim in.
Lake is 13" higher than last fall.
So far no algae - weeds are minimal.
Since month of August the weed grew a lot in low areas.
The floating weeds are the main problem at this time.
Water color gray.  Small portions started- weeds growing.
Weeds started to grow fast in east part of lake.
Water clear gray and part green.  Floating weeds.
Lake level high- water going over the dam.  Still cold 60 degrees.
Lake level is high over the dam.  The water is gray.
Lake level is high over the dam.  The water is gray.

The reason Whitewater Lake is more murky this year is due to last winter's heavy ice and snow- which retarded the growth of weeds in the lake. Therefore- the lack of weeds made the lake more murky. I base this on 10 years + experience of lake measurements.
Unusual that there is less plankton here than other sites
A lot of filamentous algae covering macrophytes.  Heron chicks close to fledging.
Approx. 8 pair of gr. bl. herons and 4 pair of gr. egrets nesting on heron island.  Filamentous algae growing on aquatic macrophytes.
Few macrophytes due to Spring chemical treatment.  Lots of filamentous algae growing on macrophytes throughout basin.
aquatic weeds down due to chem spraying
Gr. Blue Herons and Gr Egrets nesting on island
Rookery island includes both great blue herons and great egrets.  Great egrets may outnumber blue herons - would be a first that there are more great egrets.
Numerous floating mats of algae observed
Nesting island has numerous great egrets- several herons- and a few cormorants.
Thick stand of macrophytes throughout South Basin.  Not as much phytoplankton as other parts of lake.
cannot see secchi disk due to thick growth of macrophytes
Water brown due to heavy boat traffic stirring up bottom sediments.  After a boat passes certain areas- plumes of black water can be seen- indicating prop stirring up bottom sediments.

column1: Herons and egrets still nesting/raising chicks on island.
